msgid "Basic Selection"
msgstr "基本的な選択"

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:8
#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:44
msgid "Reference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:15
msgid ""
"The most common way to select an element is to :kbd:`rmb` on that item; this"
" will replace the existing selection with the new item."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:20
msgid "Adding to a Selection"
msgstr "選択を追加する"

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:22
msgid ""
"To add to the existing selection, hold down :kbd:`shift` while right "
"clicking. Clicking again on a selected item will deselect it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:25
msgid ""
"As in :guilabel:`Object` mode, there is a unique *active* element, displayed"
" in a lighter shade (in general, the last element selected). Depending on "
"the tools used, this element might be very important!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:29
msgid ""
"Note that there is no option to choose what element to select between "
"overlapping ones (like the :kbd:`alt-rmb` click in :guilabel:`Object` mode)."
" However, if you are in solid, shaded, or textured viewport shading mode "
"(not bounding box or wireframe), you will have a fourth button in the header"
" that looks like a cube, just right of the select mode ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:36
msgid ""
"When enabled, this limits your ability to select based on visible elements "
"(as if the object was solid), and prevents you from accidentally selecting, "
"moving, deleting or otherwise working on backside or hidden items."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:42
msgid "Selecting Elements in a Region"
msgstr "領域内の要素を選択する"

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:51
msgid ""
"Region selection allows you to select groups of elements within a 2D region "
"in your 3D view. The region can be either a circle or rectangle. The "
"circular region is only available in :guilabel:`Edit mode`. The rectangular "
"region, or \"\\ *Border Select* \", is available in both :guilabel:`Edit "
"mode` and :guilabel:`Object` mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:60
msgid ""
"What is selected using both these tools is affected by the :guilabel:`Limit "
"Selection to visible` feature (available under the 3D viewport) in "
":guilabel:`Solid Viewport Shading Mode`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:62
msgid "For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:64
msgid ""
"in solid shading mode and face selection mode, all faces *within* the "
"selection area will be selected;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:65
msgid ""
"whilst in the wireframe shading mode and face selection mode, only faces "
"whose handle are within the selection area will be selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:69
msgid "Rectangular region (Border select)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:71
msgid ""
":guilabel:`Border Select` is available in either :guilabel:`Edit mode` or "
":guilabel:`Object` mode. To activate the tool use the :kbd:`B`. Use "
":guilabel:`Border Select` to select a group of objects by drawing a "
"rectangle while holding down :kbd:`lmb`. In doing this you will select all "
"objects that lie within or touch this rectangle. If any object that was last"
" active appears in the group it will become selected *and* active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:79
#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:146
msgid "Start"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:79
#: ../../manual/modeling/meshes/selecting/basics.rst:146
msgid "Selecting"
